            <h2>Krishna Near Yamuna</h2>
            <p>"Krishna near Yamuna" evokes the enchanting imagery of Lord Krishna by the sacred Yamuna River, a place deeply associated with his divine pastimes. It is along the banks of the Yamuna that Krishna performed his childhood miracles, such as subduing the serpent Kaliya and playing his mesmerizing flute, captivating the Gopis and all beings around him. The Yamuna, often considered a witness to his divine love and leelas, remains a symbol of purity, devotion, and spiritual transcendence in Hindu mythology.</p>
            <iframe src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/video/2023/11/19/189828-886572705_tiny.mp4"title="krishna near yamuna" height="400px" width="720px"></iframe>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Krishna In The Forest</h2>
            <p>"Krishna in the forest" portrays the divine moments of Lord Krishna amidst the lush greenery of Vrindavan or other sacred woods. In these serene settings, Krishna is often depicted playing his flute, enchanting the animals, birds, and Gopis with his divine melody. The forest becomes a celestial playground where he performs leelas (divine pastimes), such as dancing with the Gopis (Rasa Leela) and joyfully herding cows with his friends. These depictions symbolize harmony between nature and divinity, emphasizing Krishna's role as the supreme protector and lover of all creation.</p>
